arner of 2024, alongside <i>Inside Out 2 </i>and <i>Deadpool &amp; Wolverin=
e</i>. Even if <i>Mufasa: The Lion King </i>doesn=E2=80=99t follow suit nex=
t month=E2=80=94and, yes, <i>Alice Through the Looking Glass </i>and <i>Mal=
eficent: Mistress of Evil </i>both earned noticeably less than their predec=
essors=E2=80=94Disney has reclaimed its tentpole dominance. <br/><br/>But t=
he company is relying heavily on 2010s nostalgia. Audiences showed up for n=
ew installments of Disney=E2=80=99s most popular films from the past decade=
 (as well as follow-ups to previously Fox franchises like <i>Deadpool, Alie=
n</i>, and <i>Planet of the Apes</i>), but it=E2=80=99s been 20 years since=
 Disney=E2=80=99s last successful new-to-cinema live-action
franchise, <i>National Treasure. </i>(Though if <i>Wild Hogs 2 </i>does gan=
gbusters, I guess it=E2=80=99ll only have been 18 or 19 years.) Moreover, P=
ixar=E2=80=99s <i>Coco</i>=E2=80=94released over Thanksgiving 2017=E2=80=94=
remains Hollywood=E2=80=99s last non-sequel, not-based-on-previous-I.P. ani=
mated film to top $500 million worldwide.<br/><br/>I cannot overstate the e=
xtent to which <i>Elio</i>, the original Pixar sci-fi fantasy set to open J=
une 13, is Disney=E2=80=99s most important movie next year. The current <i>=
Moana 2</i>/<i>Wicked: Part One </i>matchup implies that, if it=E2=80=99s a=
ny good, <i>Elio</i> could suffer minimal damage from opening on the same d=
ay as Universal=E2=80=99s <i>How to Train Your Dragon </i>live-action remak=
e. <i>Elemental </i>earned $342 million overseas, which was on par with the=
 $220 million=E2=80=93$370 million likes of <i>Cars, Wall-E</i>,<i> Brave</=
i>,<i> Monsters Inc.</i>, and <i>The Incredibles. </i>It was the domestic g=
ross=E2=80=94just $154 million=E2=80=94that fell short of the customary $20=
0
million=E2=80=93$240 million North American totals, inflation notwithstandi=
ng, for the average Pixar non-sequel. <br/><br/>If <i>Elio </i>can hold fir=
m overseas and play like one of those prior classics in North America, then=
 Disney will at least have a Pixar original that performs like a Pixar orig=
inal. Remember too that <i>Coco </i>only topped $800 million because of its=
 sky-high=E2=80=94and now highly unlikely=E2=80=94$189 million from China. =
Without that boost, the Thanksgiving 2017 release would have ended up in th=
e $530 million=E2=80=93$660 million ballpark alongside successful Disney to=
ons like <i>Big Hero 6,</i> <i>Ralph Breaks the Internet</i>, <i>Tangled</i=
>, and <i>Moana</i>. <br/><br/>Perhaps Covid-era movies like <i>Encanto </i=
>and <i>Soul=E2=80=94</i>along with possibly <i>Luca</i>,<i> Raya and the L=
ast Dragon</i>, and <i>Turning Red</i>=E2=80=94would have been box office t=
riples or outright home runs in other times. Perhaps Disney never really st=
opped making all-quadrant, globally appealing
original animated films but rather, temporarily undercut the distribution m=
ethod that made them possible. And with a firm 60-day window and presumed g=
oodwill from <i>Inside Out 2 </i>and <i>Moana 2</i>, maybe Disney will disc=
over, to paraphrase a line from that other Thanksgiving franchise, that it =
had the brains, heart, and courage to successfully release blockbuster anim=
ated originals all along. <br/></td>
